rs -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early 1970s, many questioned whether Aboriginal title existed in Canada and rejected the notion that Aboriginal peoples should have rights different from those of other citizens. But in 1973 the Supreme Court of Canada issued a landmark decision in the Calder case, confirming that Aboriginal title constituted a right within Canadian law. Let Right Be Done examines the doctrine of Aboriginal title thirty years later and puts the Calder case in its legal, historical, and political context, both nationally and internationally. With its innovative blend of scholarly analysis and input from many of those intimately involved in the case, this book should be essential reading for anyone interested in Aboriginal law, treaty negotiations, and the history of the "BC Indian land question."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndians of North AmericaxLand tenurezCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLegal status, laws, etczCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxClaims. 0aIndigenous peoplesxLand tenurezCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxLegal status, laws, etczCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxClaims. 7aLAW / Indigenous Peoples.2bisacsh1 aAsch, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorrows, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForest, Gérard V. La, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, Hamar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, Hamar, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGodlewska, Christina,